    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 22 @ 2016/2017",
    "Question": {
      "content": "The unit of electrical conductivity is:",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "Farad",
        "[m]²",
        "[m]⁻²",
        "[m]⁻¹"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "[m]⁻¹"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<b>Electrical conductivity (\\(\\sigma\\))</b> is defined as the reciprocal of resistivity (\\(\\rho\\)).<br><br>• Unit of \\(\\rho\\): Ohm-meter (\\(\\Omega \\cdot m\\))<br>• Thus, \\(\\sigma = \\frac{1}{\\rho}\\) has units of \\([\\Omega \\cdot m]^{-1} = [m]^{-1}\\).<br><br>Farad (a) is for capacitance, and other options are irrelevant."
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electromagnetism and Electrodynamics",
      "Current Density",
      "Electrical Conductivity"
    ]
  },
